;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@NODE ONEPLAYER "1-Player-Scenarios"

	One player scenarios work a bit differently that multiplayer scenarios. The
most important change is, that sometimes the CPU-moves are shown to you. This happens 
if certain @{"conditions" link CONDIS} are met. There are three 1player scenarios
available at the moment:

	Math-1: An invasion scenario. You attack a castle controlled by the cpu.

	Prison-1: A rescue mission, you have forces which you must release with a
	          small band of monsters.

        Distillery-1: You protect a house attacked by the cpu.
        
 	
 	All three scenarios have a time limit, and some special victory conditions.
The CPU-monsters have different 'orders' specially developed for the scenario, but
their acting is still quite random. So they do not appear in the same place in every
scenario.

	The scenarios are also quite difficult, and are currently only tested by the
coder. Even he loses frequently, so don't get sad if you don't manage at first :)
        	
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CONDIS

	While it is the cpu's turn, a text appears on the screen, reading "independent
creatures". You can hear the sound effect, so if a cpu-player opens a door, you can
hear it. So listen carefully. Also, sometimes you can actually see what is happening,
if 
	1) Your monster sees the cpu-player. Your monster must have the correct
	   facing for this, and it's sight range must be sufficient.
	2) If a cpu-player engages your monster in hand-to-hand combat, the combat
	   is shown.
	3) For both 1 and 2, the cpu player must be visible, or if it is
	   invisible, your monster must have IR-vision.
	   
	So, the cpu moves are not shown, when, for example
	
	- cpu throws a spear at you, but your monster does not see it.
	- cpu shoots you with a bow, but your monster does not see it.
	- your are targetted with a spell ...
	
	and so on. If your monster dies from a attack such as those, you do not
	see it.


@ENDNODE
;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE KOMPIS "Independent Monsters"
   
     	There are 3 different computer player allegiances in Evil. All of them are
equally intelligent, but they attack each other just as if they were human players.
These three allegiances include:
 
	@{"The normal independent monsters" link KOMPIS6}
	@{"The living dead zombies" link KOMPIS7}
	@{"The demongate gargoyles" link KOMPIS8}
  
  	The independent monsters are able to use almost all available items for your
doom. They can cast spells for their own benefit and your doom. Alone they are not
very dangerous, but if they outnumber your troops, they can be a serious threat.
    
        The CPU player does not 'think'. The monsters just run around, quaff potions,
cast peaceful spells, and collect weaponry until enemy is sighted. Then they will 
attack using all the resources they are programmed to use. 

	Sometimes, however, the CPU player has some pre-planned maneuvers. Every
1-player scenario has specific instructions for some CPU monsters, and so do a few
multiplayer scenarios, too. These instructions create different paths for the CPU
monsters to follow. In this way, the cpu player is enable to guard, invade or just
stay out of trouble. But this guiding is not the CPU's number one priority. It will
only follow pre-set instructions when it has nothing else to do. (that is, no items
to pick up, no interesting locations to go to, no enemies etc.) This means, that
despite the pre-set control data, the CPU player still acts quite randomly, not
always going the same ways over and over again.

	Also, the CPU monsters don't do things quite in the same way as human
players do. CPU players can, for example, use wands and bows directly from their
backpack. However, the CPU pays 4 extra action points for this (The price it would
cost to move the wand/bow into the monster's hand).
 
 	
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE KOMPIS6 "Normal Independent Monsters"
 
 	These independent computer-controlled monsters are present in some scenarios.
They take their turn immediately after the last participating human player. Their
only objective is to kill everyone not of their own allegiance. 
        
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE KOMPIS7 "The Living Dead"
 
	This allegiance comes into the play when the @{"NIGHT OF THE LIVING DEAD" link B8} spell is
cast. @{"The dead corpses" link CORPSES} rise to revenge, and their only purpose is to kill all monster
not of their own rotten allegiance. They are almost harmless unless there are a great
number of them.

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE KOMPIS8 "The Grotesque Gargoyles"
   
 	Independent monsters of this allegiance appear when a @{"demongate" link V7} is left
uncontrolled, or controlled by a inadept monster. If a @{"gargoyle" link GARGOYLE} steps out of the
gate without being instantly commanded, it becomes independent, and wants to kill
all monsters not of its own allegiance. Naturally, if these gargoyles could somehow
possess other monsters, it is possible to have others than just gargoyles in this
allegiance. 

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ATTRIBUTES "Monster Attributes"

	In addition of Action Points, Health Value and Mana, all monsters have different
physical attributes.
       
	STRENGTH: The ability to carry and throw things. Also, modifies inflicted
		  damage. Varies from 1 to about 15
	
	DEXTERITY: The ability to hit targets in all forms of combat. Varies from
		   0 to about 60
	   
	INTELLIGENCE: The ability to resist spells, and regenerate spent mana points.
		      Varies from 0 to about 100. Monsters regenerate intelligence/10
		      points of mana every turn.
	 
	MACHO BONUS: The ability to resist pain. Varies from 0 to about 10. The	value
		     of macho bonus is directly subtracted from battle damage.
		     
	REGENERATION: The amount of hitpoints regenerated in a turn. Varies from 0 to
		      about 40.
		     
	MAGIC ABILITY: The spell casting knowledge of a monster. Varies from 0 to 6.
	 	       (0=Can not cast spells, 6=Can cast up to the Violet level)
	 	    
	@{"MAGIC RESISTANCE:" link MAGICPROT} The natural magic protection. Varies from 0 to 6. 0 means
			  no protection at all. Protection levels beyond 3 can only
			  be achieved via the use of magical consumables.
  
  	SIGHT RANGE: The number of square the monster is able to see. Varies from 1 to 25
              			  
	These attribute values can not be seen in the game, but they do affect it
in many ways.

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE SAVE "Loading And Saving Game"
 
 	Saving Game
 	-----------
 	           
 	At the beginning of the player number 1's turn, you are granted an opportunity 
to save the current game. To do so, press 'S' when it is asked for. Then, enter a path
and a name for the savegame, then press return when you are ready. If the save was
succesful, you will see a 'OK' message, in case of an error, you will hear a sound
signal, and get to edit the name again.

	The game saves the savefiles into Save-directory in Evil: . When you wish
to load a saved game, just launch Evil from WB, click on the 'load saved' and pick
the game. Unfortunately, for now, there is no delete-button, so you must delete
the old savefiles by yourself, or to save over them. Maybe a delete-button will be
included in a really boring and rainy day with no money or anything.

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ITEMS "Items"

	There are lots of different items in Evil. The purpose of some is obvious, but
for some more peculiar items, it is not...

	@{" Consumables " link CONSUMABLES }
	@{" Armors " link ARMORS }
	@{" Weapons " link WEAPONS }
	@{" Mines and Shovel " link MINES }
	@{" Bugs " link BUGS }
	@{" Cauldrons&Compounds " link CAULDRONS }
	@{" Bombs and Grenades " link BOMBS }
	@{" Corpses " link CORPSES }
	@{" Treasure Items " link TREASURES }
	@{" Scrolls " link SCROLLS }
	@{" Magic Wand " link MAGIC }
	@{" Other Magic Stuff " link SPELLCASTERS }
	
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CONSUMABLES "Consumable Stuff"

	Quite often, you are able to find stuff that can be somehow consumed. This
includes everything between bananas and syringes. Some of these edibles heal your
monster, while some of them might be serious intoxicants. Some consumables are magic,
and they can give your monster a magic @{"state" link STATES}, for example,invisibility.

	Consumables are consumed using the right mousebutton over the consumable item,
which is located in your monster's @{"hand" link ITEMBX}.

	But a word of caution! Sometimes even the nicest looking potions can be
proven to contain most evil and utterly malevolent forces :).

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE WEAPONS "Weapons"

	There are two different weapon categories in Evil. The melee weapons, and the 
long ranged weapons. Some of these items might be magic. If they are, the 
@{"level of the magic" link MAGIC} is shown after the name of the weapon. Non-magical items
can also be magically @{"enchanted" link Y8}.
       
       	The Melee Weapons
	-----------------
	
	These are the basic melee weapons, such as swords, daggers and axes. They can
require your monster to use either one or two hands to wield the weapon. The
main purpose of these items is to kill your enemies. To do this, you should put
these items in your @{"monster's hands" link ITEMBX}, and initiate @{"close combat" link CLOSEC}.

	The Long Ranged Weapons
	-----------------------
	
	These inculde bows, crossbows and the hat. They are used in the normal way,
just put the item in your monster's @{"hand-box" link ITEMBX}, and use the right mouse button
over the weapon's image.
  
  
	NOTE: All items can be used as long ranged weapons. Just @{"throw" link ICONS} them
at your enemies. Naturally, melee weapons inflict more damage than say, potions.
	
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE MINES "Mines and Shovel"

	One of the most effective ways to block passage to a certain area is to use
landmines. There are two different mines in Evil, the anti-personnel mine and the
anti-tank mine. Both of these items are used in the @{"normal way" link ITEMBX}. This
causes your monster to deploy the mine right in front of it. The mine is now active, and
will detonate immediately when stepped on by a monster of ANY allegiance. Non-Material
monsters will not detonate mines. Explosions will detonate all mines inside the blast
radius.
  
	Most of the time, you will want your mines to be hidden. The shovel is a perfect
item for this, for it allows you to hide items that are located in front of your
monster. Use the shovel with the right mousebutton, and if the square is suitable for
digging, the item(s) will disappear from the map. They are now hidden, and can be made
visible using the @{"search-icon" link ICONS}. Naturally, you cannot make mines visible in this 
way, because when you enter the square where a mine is hidden and activated, it will 
immediately detonate. 
  
	Another way to conceal mines is to use @{"magic" link O8}.
 	
	Pioneers are experts with mines. When @{"summoned" link V8}, they appear with a shovel and
a pile of mines.		

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE BUGS "Throwable Magic Bugs"

	These special items are used to track the movements of the enemy monsters. The
use of the bugs is easy, all you need to do is to @{"throw" link ICONS} it at your enemy. If your 
monster hits the enemy with a bug, the bug will attach itself into the enemy monster. 
Now, the enemy monster is permanently visible to your monsters, and you will ALWAYS
know where it is located. 

	The only way to get rid of these bugs is to get rid of the monster. When the
monster dies, the bug becomes inactive.

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CAULDRONS "Cauldrons And Spell Compounds"

	These items work with the @{"CONFUSING COOKING OF COMPOUNDS" link G6} spell. The spell 
compounds can be found from a certain type of bushes, and the cauldron are usually found
inside chests etc.
 
 	A filled cauldron has unlimited charges, and generally stronger effects than
the normal consumable items. The only way to get rid of a filled cauldron is to use
the @{"throw icon" link ICONS}. When a filled cauldron is throwed it becomes empty.
 
 	The effect of a cauldron depends of the spell compound you used to create it.

	Compound			Cauldron
	--------			--------

	Big Blue Berries		Invisibility Cauldron 	
	Ominous Mushroom		Protection Cauldron
	Weird Smelling Leaf		Cannabis Cauldron
	Big Brown Nut			Strength Cauldron
	Edelweiss			Dexterity Cauldron
	Ominous Berries			Macho Cauldron
    	
	Nitro				Explosive Cauldron - Cannot be consumed, 
					explodes when thrown or used. (a trap)	
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE BOMBS "Bombs and Grenades"

	Bombs
	-----
	
	These items are simple explosives, that are @{"thrown" link ICONS} towards your enemies. They
explode immediately on impact, i.e. when thrown.
 
  	Grenades
  	--------
   	
 	Grenades are a bit more complex explosives than the Bombs. They need to be
primed before they explode. If you wish to prime a grenade, you need to have it in
your hand, and click right mouse button on top of it. Then use the arrow keys to set
the timer, and left mouse button to activate the grenade. The timer counts the small
sub-turns you and the participating players take. For example, if the timer is set to
be 0, the grenade will explode immediately when you end your turn. If the timer was set
to be 1, the grenade would explode when the next player ends his turn. 
 
 	Most often you propably want to set the timer to be 0, for the simpliest use.
The @{"IMMEDIATE ITEM DELIVERY" link R5} spell works exceptionally well with the grenades... 

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE CORPSES "- You wanna see em'?  -The What?   -The Cooorpseees"
  
	When the battle goes on, it is normal that lots of corpses start to appear.
These stiffs might look harmless, because they are already dead, right ? Wrong. The
dead might not stay dead for long, if the @{"NIGHT OF THE LIVING DEAD" link B8} spell should be
cast. Also, corpses can be reanimated to serve you as zombies, with the use of the
@{"ASTONISHING ANIMATION OF CORPSES" link Y7}-spell.
 
	Also, because the corpses are quite large items, they weight a lot. Thus they
are deadly if throwed at enemies by strong monsters.
 
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE TREASURES "Treasure Items"

 	In some scenarios, there might be special items that might cause one of the
participating sides to win the match. Sometimes these items are 'treasure items', that
can not be transported by means of magic. Also, if your monster walks into a portal
with a treasure-item in its backpack, the item is automatically dropped before entering
the portal. The same happens with the use of teleportation spells.

 	Treasure items were created, because the magic spells of Evil allow very quick
transport of items around the map, and it would be almost impossible to design
scenarios with important items as objectives.
 
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE SCROLLS "Scrolls"
 
  	Scrolls are created by the @{"SCROLL OF SERIOUS SCRIBBLING" link R3}-spell. They are very
useless, but good for sending taunts and threats to your enemies. Also, they can be
used to appeal into your enemies curiousity.
 
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE SPELLCASTERS "Items That Contain Specific Spells"
 
  	Some special items can cast spells. When your monster uses such an item, it
is able to cast a spell inside the item without losing mana or without having any
knowledge of magic. Spellcasting items are activated in the normal way.
 
 	Some spellcating items might have spells in them that can not be found from
the magic menu. Some spellcasters allow you to choose a target for the spell, while
some might target yourself immediately. Some spellcasters tell you the name of the
spell, which they contain, while some do not.
 
 	A good example of a spellcaster that lets you know the name of the spell is
the wand of missiles. Also, a good example of a spellcaster that does not tell you
its spell are the anomalous ankhs. The use of such items can be dangerous, but also
very beneficial.

	@{"The harp" link HARP}
@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@NODE HARP "The Harp"

	This interesting piece of musical equipment first appeared in the V1.25. All
monsters who have at least one arm, can play the harp. This terrible music can have
a fatal effect on monsters who disagree with the musicant's taste. 

	Musicians usually play music, which corresponds to their intelligence. Very
smart characters enjoy complex music, while stupid ones like to listen simple 'plings'
and 'plongs'. (It should be noted that the coder's record collection contains mainly
techno music at this point. :) ) Anyway, it is quite obvious that the harp can be used
as an effective weapon against monsters with different taste of music.

	The harp has a range of about 10 squares. If there is an obstacle in the way,
the music can not be heard. There is an exception; inside a 3-square-radius ALL 
monsters hear the music, even through obstacles. Disabled (passed out) monsters do 
not care for music. Intoxicants of all sorts are ignored, if taken reasonably. The 
music is considered to cover the lower half of the magic, that is, it is of the
3rd level - yellow magic. This means that every monster is affected, unless they
have obtained special protection via potions or something. The possible damage due
to the music is not lowered by any faction.

@ENDNODE
;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE STATES "Magic States"

	During the play, your monsters can be affected by magic. They might quaff a
strength potion, or be targetted by an invisibilty spell. When something like this
happens, the monster is said to be under a specific state. This state is shown after
the name of the monster in brackets. For example, if a brave knight drinks a bottle
of booze, his new state would be 'drunken' and shown like this :

	BRAVE KNIGHT (DRUNKEN)
   
   	The monsters of Evil may have only one magical state active at a time. If you
try to use several state modifiers simultaneously, you will get an error message. If
you happen to accidentally gain an unwanted state, you can cancel its effects via the
use of the @{"SUDDEN SOBERING OF SERVANTS" link Y6}-spell.

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE COMBAT "Combat"

	Monsters can kill their enemies in a number of ways:
	
	@{"Close Combat" link CLOSEC}
	@{"Long Range Combat" link LONGC}
	@{"Magic" link MAGIC}

	Monsters can also try to defend themselves:
	
	@{"Saving Action Points" link SAVINGPOINTS}
	@{"Magic Protection" link MAGICPROT}
	@{"Armors" link ARMORS}

@ENDNODE

;--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE MAGIC "Magic"

	Magic in Evil is divided up into 6 different levels. These levels
are represented by colors: Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Blue and Violet.
Red magic is the easiest to handle and Violet is the most difficult.
Wizards and other spellcasters wear different colored robes. These colors
usually indicate the highest level of magic the character can handle, i.e.
a yellow colored mage could cast spells of red,orange and yellow level but
no higher. 

	Casting Spells :
 		
	The spells are cast by using a magical wand. Put it into your
character's hand and use right button to see the magic menu. Choose a spell
by using the left mouse button, right button aborts. Note that some 
@{"wands or other items" link SPELLCASTERS} contain certain spells in them, and are only able to 
cast that spell only (but you don't lose any mana). Such items are usually named 
as 'wand of fireballs' or something similiar. 
 	
	We have tried to make every spell useful. In some games there's 
stupid spells nobody would never cast in serious combat. If we discover
that none of us is using a certain spell, we'll do something to make it
better... lower the manaprice or boost the effect, whatever. Obviously a
master sorcerer doesn't cast red level spells very often, but the point is,
that a red level illusionist finds all of them useful. (or at least FUN)

	Each spell level contains 8 spells.
 	
	@{"Red" link REDSPELLS}
	@{"Orange" link ORANGESPELLS}
	@{"Yellow" link YELLOWSPELLS}
	@{"Green" link GREENSPELLS}
	@{"Blue" link BLUESPELLS}
	@{"Violet" link VIOLETSPELLS}
@ENDNODE

